snippet: The White House has pushed to develop new options that could help deter Tehran without escalating into a full-out war.
lead_paragraph: Good Monday morning. Here are some of the stories making news in Washington and politics today.
abstract: The White House has pushed to develop new options that could help deter Tehran without escalating into a full-out war.
headline_main: On Politics: U.S. Working on Clandestine Plans for Iran

snippet: Mr. Biden said his words about Southern segregationists who served with him in the Senate were misunderstood and stopped just short of an apology.
lead_paragraph: COLUMBIA, S.C. — Joseph R. Biden Jr. on Saturday sought to tamp down anger over his praise for the bygone civility of a Senate that included notorious segregationists, stopping just short of an apology while asserting that his reference to never being called “boy” by one of the senators was not racial in nature.
abstract: Mr. Biden said his words about Southern segregationists who served with him in the Senate were misunderstood and stopped just short of an apology.

snippet: The president, like his opposition, may be underestimating his ability to win.
lead_paragraph: The night before the 2016 presidential election, I thought Hillary Clinton would win and Donald Trump would go down to a convincing defeat. I was wrong.

snippet: Can his rivals fracture or overwhelm his coalition?
lead_paragraph: Where politicians are concerned, especially aging and garrulous ones, it may be a mistake to attribute to strategy what can be chalked up to simple fecklessness. But amid the shambolic style of Joe Biden’s front-running campaign to date, the flip-flops and apparent gaffes, it’s possible to discern a certain method, a general plan for how the candidate hopes to run for president: by changing positions on issues when he needs to, but without betraying his own amour-propre, his sense of what being Joe Biden is supposed to mean.
abstract: Can his rivals fracture or overwhelm his coalition?

snippet: Will the Democratic Party banish its democratic instincts?
lead_paragraph: For several years I had a regular lunch date with an Iranian diplomat — I suspect his real profession was otherwise — who worked out of the Islamic Republic’s mission to the United Nations.
